<font color="#FF0000">TO WILLIAM DONALD</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jun  3  6:15:35 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I think it is easy to have priorities in life, such as the ones you describe, which like the war we fought in - seem beyond our control.<br><br>
Don't feel bad about giving these priorities your utmost attention. There is another way to &quot;memorialize&quot; the Fallen and that is to live every precious minute. These &quot;minutes&quot; were stolen from our war dead.<br><br>
As for your &quot;dark thoughts&quot; and your &quot;fears&quot;, I don't believe there is a way that they can be totally shed. We learn to live with them and to pick up the burden and carry it each day.<br><br>
The thing that has helped me most of all is by talking about Vietnam. There are different places on the Internet where I am able to unload or to tell of how I experienced something there.<br><br>
In this group, for example, understanding has been achieved among people who have  or had very diverse points of view and opinions. We are able to look back through all of the documentation on this site - much of it painful - and see that we have made real progress. When each person looks at his or her particular contribution there should be a sense of great accomplishment. These can be viewed as the &quot;bricks&quot; you refer to. We all agree that there should never be another Vietnam.<br><br>
The point I am making is that there needs to be a dialogue between people and a willingness to learn. Looking back on the 1960's, can we honestly say that there was an effort by anyone to listen and understand? This is not to say that there wasn't a need to express opinions back then. There was. But, now there is a need for people to come together, to lay bare their souls (speak from their guts as Doc Spatz would say), and to put the bitterness behind them. I sincerely believe that the bitterness is one thing that can be done away with.<br><br>
I can't speak for anyone but myself. So, as a vet of Vietnam, I now realize that what I have to say, is by no means the final, profound word - but is a contribution to the common good, nevertheless.<br><br>
There will always be that sense of loss or &quot;waste&quot; as you state. The present offers all who lived during those times and who contribute to this site an opportunity. This site gives all who participate a real sense of accomplishment. That is something that we didn't have when we came home from Vietnam  - a sense of accomplishment.<br><br>
If you feel caught up in the trappings of life, then this site offers you a chance to leave those trappings for a while. There are many here who view this little corner of the Internet as being an important part of their lives. It comes from participation.<br><br>
Welcome Home to you William.<br><br>
Tom Dier
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


